PART I. ASSOCIATION RULES MINING

Data Preparation

We begin by preparing our data to be in the proper format for association rules mining. Our main transaction file dream cafe transactions.txt, is loaded in as a dataframe so we can do some cleanup, instead of using the file as input directly into the read.transactions() function.

We remove the size from the item code since it’s not very relevant, and also add the item names and categories to the dataset from the file menu items and codes.csv. This was given as a pdf file, but we also encoded it as a csv for easier use in the analysis.

The final cleaned transaction data now has the following columns, and is written out to dream cafe transactions_clean.txt:

  • item_code - unique Item Code of a Product
  • trans_id - unique Transaction ID of a transaction (now cleaned up and size removed from beverages)
  • date - date of when a transaction occurred
  • time - time of when a transaction occurred
  • qty- quantity of the item purchased in a given transaction
  • Category - general product category of a product (e.g. CAKES, ESPRESSO DRINK, etc)
  • Item - the item name corresponding to the Item Code
raw_trans <- read.delim(file = "dream cafe transactions.txt", sep = "\t")
# We encoded the menu from the pdf file in a csv file for ease of interpretations later on.
menu <- read.csv("menu items and codes.csv")

# Separate into item code and size
raw_trans %>% separate(item_code, into=c("item_code", "size"), sep=" - ") -> raw_trans

# Drop Size Column to get Clean data
clean_trans <- subset(raw_trans, select = -size)
clean_trans <- merge(clean_trans, menu, by.x="item_code", by.y="Item_Code")
# Write out to file
write.csv(clean_trans, "dream cafe transactions_clean.txt", sep="\t", row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)

# Display sample cleaned data
clean_trans %>% arrange(trans_id) %>% head(10)

We do some initial exploration of our transaction data for the dataset description and EDA.

Let’s see the scope of our transaction dates by getting the min and maximum transaction date:

clean_trans %>% 
  mutate(Date = as.POSIXct(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d")) %>%
  group_by(Date) %>% 
  select(Date) %>%
  # with_ties = FALSE so no dates are repeated
  slice_max(order_by = Date, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) -> trans_dates

# Get the earliest and latest transaction dates
# Minnimum Date
head(trans_dates, 1)
# Maximum Date
tail(trans_dates, 1)

And we can do the same for transaction times, to see the earliest and latest logged transaction times within these dates.

clean_trans %>% 
  arrange(time) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  select(time) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = time, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) -> trans_times

# Get the earliest and latest transaction times
# Minimum Transaction Time
head(trans_times, 1)
# Maximum Transaction Time
tail(trans_times, 1)

Since we plan to explore the store transactions over different time periods within the operating hours, we can also group our transactions by hour and see the general trend of traffic in the cafe by hour. Are there any patterns in transactions over the course of the day? Are there certain peak hours? We can use this information to later decide on how we want to group our transactions by time period.

clean_trans %>% 
  # Adding an arbitrary date - set all dates to be the same for time comparisons
  mutate(time2 = dmy_hms(paste0("01/01/00 ",time))) %>%
  # Get hour of each timestamp only
  mutate(hour = lubridate::floor_date(time2, "1 hour")) %>%
  group_by(hour) %>%
  summarise(trans_count = n_distinct(trans_id)) -> trans_hourly

trans_hourly

Association Rules Mining

On the entire dataset

We first mine association rules from the entire transaction set - without filtering for time periods.

We use our clean transaction file from earlier as input into the read_transactions() function from arules, and identify the transaction and item ID columns in the cols argument as trans_id and item_code respectively.

cafe_trans <- read.transactions(file = "dream cafe transactions_clean.txt", format = "single", 
                                   sep = ",", header = T, cols = c(2,1), quote = NULL)

cafe_trans

Running the association rules on our data…

coffee_apriori <- apriori(data = cafe_trans, 
                          parameter = list(support = 0.01, confidence = 0.4,
                                           minlen = 2, maxlen = 5, originalSupport = F))

Filter rules dataframe to get corresponding rules. For brevity when recommending product bundles, we select the top 3 rules according to our criteria.

# Create Menu Data Objects for Recoding
codes <- menu$Item_Code
names <- menu$Item
categories <- menu$ï..Category

# Filter association rules
rules_df %>% 
  # High Frequency, Positive Association
  filter(lift > 1) %>% 
  # Good Quality Rules First
  arrange(desc(support)) %>%
  # Clean Up Data
  mutate(lhs=gsub("[{}]", "", lhs),
         rhs=gsub("[{}]", "", rhs)) %>% 
 separate("lhs", sep=",", into=c("lhs_p1", "lhs_p2", "lhs_p3")) %>%
  # Get just the top 5
  head(10)  -> rules_df_clean

rules_df_clean %>%
  # Recode Item Codes for easier Interpretation
  mutate(lhs_p1 = names[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$lhs_p1, which=c("both")), codes)],
         lhs_p2 = names[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$lhs_p2, which=c("both")), codes)],
         lhs_p3 = names[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$lhs_p3, which=c("both")), codes)],
         rhs = names[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$rhs, which=c("both")), codes)])

We can also examine the item categories to get the general behaviors/patterns across the transaction set.

rules_df_clean %>%
  # Get Item Categories for Interpretations
  mutate(lhs_p1 = categories[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$lhs_p1, which=c("both")), codes)],
         lhs_p2 = categories[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$lhs_p2, which=c("both")), codes)],
         lhs_p3 = categories[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$lhs_p3, which=c("both")), codes)],
         rhs = categories[match(trimws(rules_df_clean$rhs, which=c("both")), codes)])

Splitting Data by Time

The stores are open from 7:00AM to 11:00PM. Next, let us explore the associations when we separate our transactions by time of day.

First, let’s visualize the transaction volume hourly from the store, so we can maybe get an idea on how time affects our transactions in Dream Cafe. For this, we use the trans_hourly dataframe from earlier, which contains the count of transactions grouped by hour.

# Create annotations for dataframe
label <- data.frame(
  hour <- c(dmy_hms("01/01/00 15:00:00"),
            dmy_hms("01/01/00 08:00:00"),
            dmy_hms("01/01/00 12:00:00"),
            dmy_hms("01/01/00 19:00:00")),
  trans_count <- c(2350,
                   945,
                   1537,
                   1325),
  labeltext <- c("Peak Hour: 3PM", 
                 "Breakfast Rush: 8AM",
                 "Lunch Rush: 12PM",
                 "Dinner Rush: 7PM")
)
# Visualize Transaction Hourly Trend
ggplot(trans_hourly, aes(x=hour, y=trans_count)) +
  geom_area(col="mediumseagreen", fill="mediumseagreen", alpha=0.5) +
  geom_point(data=label, aes(x=hour, y=trans_count), col="mediumseagreen") +
  geom_label(data=label, aes(label=labeltext), nudge_y = 160, nudge_x=800) + 
  labs(x = "Hour of Transaction",
       y = "Total Transaction Count",
       title = "Dream Cafe Transaction Volume by Hour") +
  theme_bw()

We can see three main peaks in terms of transaction volume throughout the day. Very clearly, Dream Cafe’s peak hour is 3PM - perhaps many customers come here for afternoon snacks. After that, we can see a peak during lunch at 12PM, and one at dinner at 7PM. For breakfast, if you can consider it a peak, there is one at around 8AM. As expected as well, we see low traffic at the start and end of the day.

From these patterns, we are motivated to split up our data later on into four periods based on the peaks: breakfast, lunch, merienda, and dinner. We want each period to contain the peaks we mentioned earlier. These periods are as follows:

  • Breakfast Time - 7:00AM - 11:00AM
  • Lunch Time - 11:00AM - 2:00PM
  • Merienda Time - 2:00PM - 6:00PM
  • Dinner Time - 6:00PM - 11:00PM
# Visualize Transaction Hourly Trend
ggplot(trans_hourly, aes(x=hour, y=trans_count)) +
  annotate("rect", fill="plum1", alpha=0.3,
           xmin = dmy_hms("01/01/00 07:00:00"),
           xmax = dmy_hms("01/01/00 11:00:00"),
           ymin = -Inf,
           ymax = Inf) +
  annotate("rect", fill="skyblue1", alpha=0.35,
           xmin = dmy_hms("01/01/00 11:00:00"),

We apply these time intervals to our data and create separate datasets for each time period below.

# Helper Function to filter transaction data by a specific lubridate interval
filter_time <- function(interval) {
  clean_trans %>%
  mutate(time2 = format(ymd_hms(paste(date,time)), "%H:%M:%S")) %>%
  # Adding an arbitrary date - set all dates to be the same for time comparisons
  mutate(time2 = dmy_hms(paste0("01/01/00 ",time2))) %>% 
  # Filter transactions within the interval only
  filter(time2 %within% interval) %>%
  dplyr::select(-time2) -> filtered
  
  return(filtered)
}

# Create Lubridate Intervals for each Time Period
breakfast_time <- dmy_hms("1/1/00 07:00:00") %--% dmy_hms("1/1/00 10:59:59")
lunch_time <- dmy_hms("1/1/00 11:00:00") %--% dmy_hms("1/1/00 13:59:59")
merienda_time <- dmy_hms("1/1/00 14:00:00") %--% dmy_hms("1/1/00 17:59:59")
dinner_time <- dmy_hms("1/1/00 18:00:00") %--% dmy_hms("1/1/00 22:59:59")

# Create tibbles/df for each time period
breakfast_trans <- filter_time(breakfast_time)
lunch_trans <- filter_time(lunch_time)
merienda_trans <- filter_time(merienda_time)
dinner_trans <- filter_time(dinner_time)

# Write out to text files as input to read.transactions()
write.csv(breakfast_trans, "breakfast_trans.txt", row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)
write.csv(lunch_trans, "lunch_trans.txt", row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)
write.csv(merienda_trans, "merienda_trans.txt", row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)
write.csv(dinner_trans, "dinner_trans.txt", row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE)

head(bfast_rules_df)

We arrange the rules by support to get the most popular item combinations.

# Arrange Rules DF by support
bfast_rules_df %>% arrange(desc(support))

We then select our best rules. For this, we want our lift greater than 1, and to have as much support as possible, since more frequent item sets will be more profitable.

bfast_rules_df %>% 
  filter(lift > 1) %>%
  arrange(desc(support)) %>%
  # Clean Up Data
  mutate(lhs=gsub("[{}]", "", lhs),
        rhs=gsub("[{}]", "", rhs)) %>% 
  separate("lhs", sep=",", into=c("lhs_p1", "lhs_p2", "lhs_p3"))  %>%
  # Get top 10 rules, choose best 3 from here
  head(10) -> bfast_rules_final
## Warning: Expected 3 pieces. Missing pieces filled with `NA` in 49 rows [1, 2, 3,
## 4, 12, 15, 19, 21, 22, 25, 28, 29, 30, 33, 38, 42, 43, 44, 52, 53, ...].
bfast_rules_final %>% 
  #Recode Item Codes for easier Interpretation
  mutate(lhs_p1 = names[match(trimws(bfast_rules_final$lhs_p1, which=c("both")), codes)],
         lhs_p2 = names[match(trimws(bfast_rules_final$lhs_p2, which=c("both")), codes)],
         lhs_p3 = names[match(trimws(bfast_rules_final$lhs_p3, which=c("both")), codes)],
         rhs = names[match(trimws(bfast_rules_final$rhs, which=c("both")), codes)])

We can see that generally, espresso drinks and frappes are quite popular during breakfast time. The blueberry muffin, a typical breakfast food is also present in the most popular combination.

Sorting the lunch bundle combinations by the support to get the most popular combinations.

most_popular_pair_lunch <- lunch_rules_df %>% arrange(desc(support))
most_popular_pair_lunch

Frequency - a bundle is more profitable if it is bought more often.

The most popular pair for lunch is a classic sausage roll and a vanilla caffe frappe. In terms of the item categories, bread/pastries/sandwiches with ice-blended drinks (frappes) are the most popular choice for lunch. This is a combination that is more on the heavy side which suggests that customers are looking for something filling for lunch.

For the most likely items to be bought together,

most_likely_bundle <- lunch_rules_df %>% arrange(desc(lift))
most_likely_bundle

Customers who buy bread/pastries/sandwich and espresso drinks are most likely to buy a cafe americano. This can be an potential add on/upselling opportunity to increase the number of items included in a bundle and thus increase the profits. But, support for these transactions are not that high so more focus will still be given to the items with a higher level of support and a lift that is greater than 1.

Get the best 3 rules from the top 10:

lunch_rules_df %>%

Sorting the dinner bundle combinations by the support:

most_popular_pair_dinner <- dinner_rules_df %>% arrange(desc(support))
most_popular_pair_dinner

Similar to lunch, when arranged by support, vanilla caffe frappe is the top RHS drink of choice for dinner transactions.

Customers in 3 out of the top 5 most popular dinner pair transactions ordered DCCAKE (Dayap Cheesecake) which is one of the cafe’s specialty items.

The most popular dinner combination is Dayap Cheesecake, Iced cafe latte and vanilla caffe frappe.

The most popular dinner items are cakes (Dayap Cheesecake, Banoffee Pie, Classic Chocolate cake) which suggests that people have a more filling dinner elsewhere then they go to the cafe for their specialty cakes/desserts. This is also supported by the top choice of Vanilla Frappe for dinner.

Thus, promoting cakes and vanilla frappes for dinner time might be more profitable since this is what the customers are looking for.

For the most likely items to be bought together,

most_likely_bundle <- dinner_rules_df %>% arrange(desc(lift))
most_likely_bundle

If we want to increase the item count in a transaction, we consider the confidence levels because a high confidence means that if the customer bought the LHS, they’re more likely to buy the RHS thus potentially increasing the profitability.

Sorting by the confidence levels,

most_confident_bundle <- dinner_rules_df %>% arrange(desc(confidence))
most_confident_bundle

But, items with the highest confidence levels are also more complicated bundles (4 to 5 items). Furthermore, in the items sorted by the descending order of support levels, even if the confidence is not that high, customers are already more likely to buy a Vanilla Frappe which suggests that upselling vanilla frappes as an add on if the customer already bought 2 or 3 items might not be the best strategy.

Display top 10 rules by support with lift > 1.

dinner_rules_df %>%
  filter(lift > 1) %>%
  arrange(desc(support)) %>%
  head(10) %>%
  # Clean Up Data
  mutate(lhs=gsub("[{}]", "", lhs),
        rhs=gsub("[{}]", "", rhs)) %>% 
  separate("lhs", sep=",", into=c("lhs_p1", "lhs_p2", "lhs_p3"))  %>%
  # Get top 10 rules, choose best 3 from here
  head(10) -> dinner_rules_final
